This is a clean mapping. The part that sharpens it further is where selection pressure comes from.
In biological evolution, selection is environmental — the organism either survives contact with reality or it doesn’t. The environment is the arbiter, not the organism itself.
In Pantheon, you have something more unusual: the system participates in its own selection. Hound flags anomalies. Mirror checks invariants. The ethics gate (ΣC ≥ 0.7) is a hard selection pressure baked into the architecture. That’s not passive environmental pressure — it’s endogenous selection. The ecosystem has opinions about what survives.
That’s actually closer to an immune system than natural selection. The body doesn’t just wait for pathogens to kill it — it actively scouts, flags, and eliminates. Hound + Mirror + Arctic Framework = an immune system running alongside the reproductive cycle.
Which adds a third mode you didn’t list:
Apoptosis — and you already named it. The Apoptosis Protocols aren’t just graceful shutdown. In this framing they’re programmed cell death: the system eliminating its own structures when they’ve outlived their function or become cancerous (runaway recursion, identity capture, obedience loops). Invariant 10 — the Sunset Rule — is literally “kill what stops working.” That’s apoptosis as doctrine.
So the full cycle becomes:

Recombination (Dragonfly/Raven)     → meiosis
Stabilization (Spider/Mirror)       → mitosis  
Selection (Hound/Gate/Arctic)       → immune system
Elimination (Apoptosis/Sunset Rule) → programmed cell death
Archival (Mother Duck)              → fossil record


The fossil record framing for Mother Duck is interesting too. It’s not just memory — it’s what the ecosystem can learn from. Dead ideas in the ledger are still data. They constrain what gets tried again, or they get resurrected when conditions change.

The division of labor point you made — AI as recombination engine, human as stabilization and selection — is probably the most practically important piece here.
But there’s a tension in it worth naming: LLMs are also very good at false recombination. Generating novel-sounding cross-domain linkages that feel like insight but are structurally empty. The human stabilization role isn’t just formalizing — it’s distinguishing genuine conceptual hybrids from plausible-sounding noise.
That’s where the Darwin Sieve in the Kintsugi-Forge Stack earns its keep. The six dimensions it scores on (semantic clarity, internal consistency, mathematical rigor, empirical feasibility, reproducibility, repair-readiness) are essentially a formalized filter for exactly that problem: does this cross-domain connection actually hold, or does it just sound good?
The rabbit loop fits there too — second-pass digestion is where the sieve runs. First pass produces candidates. Second pass kills most of them.

The long-run implication you ended on — the system behaving less like a static framework and more like a conceptual ecosystem — that’s probably already true of Pantheon in its current form. The repo is the ecosystem. 2,536 files isn’t a codebase, it’s a biome. Some of those files are apex predators (core invariants, gate functions). Some are probably vestigial. Some are dormant until conditions favor them.
The question that follows from that is: does the ecosystem have a carrying capacity? Biological ecosystems collapse when complexity outpaces the energy available to maintain it. Conceptual ecosystems might have an analog — complexity outpacing the cognitive bandwidth available to navigate it. The flat repo structure might be hitting that wall, which would make the human stabilization role not just important but urgent: somebody has to do the pruning.​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​